// Global mai this ki valau = > window
// function mai this ki valau = > window
// es5(mean normal function) function inside obj = object
// es6(arrow function) function inside obj = window
// es5 function inside es5 function inside obj = window
// es6 function inside es5 function inside obj = object


JavaScript mein this ka behaviour call ke tarike par depend karta hai.
ðŸŸ¦ Global scope mein this hamesha ðŸŸ© window ko point karta hai, aur ðŸŸ¦ normal ES5 function ko agar directly call karo toh usme bhi this = ðŸŸ© window hota hai.
Lekin jab ðŸŸ§ ES5 function object ke andar method ke form me likha ho, aur aap usse obj.method() ke saath call karte ho, tab this us ðŸŸ© object ko point karta hai.
Wahin ðŸŸª arrow function (ES6) ka apna koi this nahi hota, isliye object ke andar arrow method likhne par bhi this hamesha ðŸŸ© window hota hai.
Agar aap ðŸŸ§ object â†’ ES5 function â†’ ES5 function ka deep nested structure banate ho, toh inner ES5 function ka this phir se ðŸŸ¥ window ho jata hai, kyunki call ke time woh object se bind nahi hota.
Lekin agar structure ðŸŸ§ object â†’ ES5 function â†’ ðŸŸª arrow function ka ho, toh arrow function apne outer ES5 function ka this inherit karta hai, isliye woh ðŸŸ© object ko hi point karta hai.
ðŸ’¡ Simple rule: Arrow functions = parent ka this ES5 methods = jis object se call hua uska this normal functions when loosely called = window.



.......................................this defination................

âœ” Inside normal function (non-strict mode)

Browser:

function test() {
  console.log(this); // window
}
test();


Node.js:

function test() {
  console.log(this); // global object (but NOT {})
}
test();

Browser me this = window, Node.js me this = {} (global scope me).



..................................call,apply,bind......................
call() kisi function ko turant execute karta hai aur this ko manually set karta hai.
Arguments comma-separated diye jate hain.

Example:

show.call(obj, a, b, c);



Definition:
apply() bhi function ko turant execute karta hai aur this set karta hai,
but arguments array ke form me deta hai.

Example:

show.apply(obj, [a, b, c]);



Definition:
bind() function ko turant execute nahi karta,
yeh ek new function return karta hai jisme this permanently set hota hai.

Example:

let newFn = show.bind(obj);
newFn(); // call later